-- в”Ђв”Ђ Actiona в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Actiona is a free, open-source, cross-platform desktop automation tool that lets users build and run action lists to control the mouse, keyboard, windows, and files, either with a visual drag-and-drop editor or JavaScript scripting.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$open-source$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2005, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$Solo maintainer with community contributors (open-source project, no company)$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$France (distributed open-source project)$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Actiona Review 2026: Free Open-Source Desktop Automation Tool$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Actiona is a free, open-source automation tool for Windows and Linux that scripts mouse clicks, keystrokes, and desktop tasks. Read features, pricing, and FAQs.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Actiona, formerly known as Actionaz, is a free and open-source task automation application for desktop computers, originally created in 2005 by French software engineer Jonathan Mercier-Ganady and still maintained by him with community contributions. The software is licensed under the GNU General Public License version 3, with some bundled components under MIT, BSD, and Creative Commons licenses. Actiona is not a commercial product; there is no company behind it, and development is funded through voluntary donations and sponsorships that cover server hosting and code-signing certificate costs. Actiona runs on Windows and Linux and lets users build lists of actions that emulate mouse clicks, mouse movement, keyboard presses, and text entry. Beyond input emulation, it can run system commands, open URLs, display notifications and message boxes, play sounds, search the screen for images or pixel colors, and manipulate application windows. It also supports file operations such as reading and writing text, binary, and INI files, working with the system clipboard and environment variables, copying or downloading files, and sending emails. Flow-control actions let users create loops, jump to labels, pause execution, wait for a specific window or date and time, and stop or exit a running script. Two authoring modes are available: a beginner-friendly visual editor for assembling actions via drag and drop, and a JavaScript (EcmaScript) scripting mode for advanced users who want conditional logic, custom functions, or integration with other tools. Because it requires no programming knowledge to get started, Actiona is popular for repetitive desktop chores like form filling, file organization, scheduled backups, testing UI interactions, and general keyboard-and-mouse macro recording, making it a free alternative to commercial RPA and macro tools such as AutoHotkey or UiPath for individual users. The project remains actively developed, with releases continuing into 2026, source code hosted publicly on GitHub, and a Discord community for support and discussion. Since it is entirely free and open source, Actiona has no pricing tiers, subscriptions, or enterprise licensing; anyone can download, use, modify, and redistribute it under the terms of the GPLv3 license.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '53160125-bbda-43d5-ad5c-c1b8f9543567';

