-- в”Ђв”Ђ Acumatica в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Acumatica is a cloud-based ERP platform for mid-market businesses that unifies financials, distribution, manufacturing, project accounting, and CRM, priced by resource usage rather than per-user seats.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$custom$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Custom pricing, with entry-level editions typically starting around 6,400 to 7,000 dollars per year$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2008, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$400+ employees$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Bellevue, Washington, United States$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Acumatica Review 2026: Cloud ERP Pricing, Features and Editions$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$See what Acumatica cloud ERP offers mid-market businesses, including editions, resource-based pricing, key modules, pros and cons, and frequently asked questions.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Acumatica is a cloud-based enterprise resource planning (ERP) platform aimed primarily at mid-market and growing businesses. It was founded in 2008 by ERP industry veterans, including John Howell, Serguei Beloussov, and Mike Chtchelkonogov, and is headquartered in Bellevue, Washington, in the Seattle metropolitan area, with additional offices across North America, Europe, Asia, and Australasia. The company employs more than 400 people and serves over 9,000 customers worldwide through a network of value-added resellers and partners who handle sales, implementation, and support. Acumatica's platform covers financial management, distribution and inventory, manufacturing, project accounting, construction management, retail-commerce, and customer relationship management, delivered as a unified suite that customers can adopt incrementally by application. The product is offered in five industry-oriented editions, including General Business, Distribution, Manufacturing, Construction, and Retail-Commerce, plus four licensing tiers, Essentials, Select, Prime, and Enterprise, that determine which modules and capabilities are included. What differentiates Acumatica most from typical ERP vendors is its pricing model: rather than charging per named user or per seat, Acumatica charges based on the applications a customer implements and a resource tier determined by transaction volume, data storage, and computing consumption. This lets an organization add unlimited users at no extra licensing cost, which the company markets heavily as an advantage over legacy per-seat ERP pricing. Typical annual subscription costs range widely, from roughly 6,400 to 7,000 dollars per year for small-business entry tiers, to 25,000 to 75,000 dollars per year for mid-market deployments with 50 to 200 users, up to 150,000 dollars or more per year for large enterprise implementations with heavy transaction volumes. Acumatica can be deployed as SaaS in the cloud, as a privately hosted cloud instance, or on-premise, giving customers flexibility over data residency and infrastructure control. The platform is built on a modern, open architecture with a documented API, which supports third-party integrations and industry-specific extensions built by Acumatica's partner ecosystem. Because exact costs depend heavily on modules, resource tier, and implementation partner, Acumatica does not publish a fixed price list and instead directs prospective customers to industry-specific pricing calculators or a custom quote process managed through its reseller network.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '22872790-a987-4220-a685-a1406d4edc47';

